DOCUMENT();       

loadMacros("PG.pl",
           "PGbasicmacros.pl",
           "PGchoicemacros.pl",
           "PGanswermacros.pl",
           "PGgraphmacros.pl",
           "PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl",
           "extraAnswerEvaluators.pl"
           );
       
TEXT(beginproblem()); # standard preamble to each problem.


$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$pick = random(0,1,1);
$b = non_zero_random(-9,9,1);

if ($pick == 0) {
   $eqn = "\frac{x}{(x+$b)^3}";
   $right = "INFINITY";
   $right_sym = "\infty";
   $left = "-INFINITY";
   $left_sym = "- \infty"}
else {
   $eqn = "\frac{-x}{(x+$b)^3}";
   $right = "-INFINITY";
   $left = "INFINITY";
   $right_sym = "- \infty";
   $left_sym = "\infty"};

$q = -$b;

$d[0] = .001;
$d[1] = .01;
$d[2] = .1;
$d[3] = 1;

for ($i = 0; $i <= 3; $i++){
  $x[$i] = $q+$d[$i];
  $r[$i] = round((-1)**{$pick}*$x[$i]/($x[$i]+$b)**3)};

for ($i = 0; $i <= 3; $i++){
  $z[$i] = $q-$d[3-$i];
  $l[$i] = round((-1)**{$pick}*$z[$i]/($z[$i]+$b)**3)};

BEGIN_TEXT
Question 13:
$BR
$SPACE
$BR
Let \( \displaystyle f(x) = $eqn \) and estimate the one-sided limits below.  If you need to enter \( \infty \) or \( - \infty \), enter INFINITY or -INFINITY.
$BR $SPACE $BR
a) \( \ \displaystyle \lim_{x \to $q^+} f(x) = \) \{ ans_rule(12) \}
$BR $SPACE $BR
b) \( \ \displaystyle \lim_{x \to $q^-} f(x) = \) \{ ans_rule(12) \}
$BR
END_TEXT

ANS( fun_cmp( $right, vars=>['I','N','F','T','Y']  ));   
ANS( fun_cmp( $left, vars=>['I','N','F','T','Y'] ));   

SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$BR $SPACE $BR 
$BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD
$BR 
To find \( \ \displaystyle \lim_{x \to $q^+} f(x) \) we consider what happens to the function when \( x \) is slightly larger than \( $q \).  One way to investigate this behavior is to use a table such as the one below:
$BR
$BCENTER
\{ begintable(6) \}
\{ row ( "\( x \)", "$q", @x ) \}
\{ row ( "\( f(x) \)", "Undefined", @r ) \}
\{ endtable() \}
$ECENTER
$BR
From the table we can see that \( \ \displaystyle \lim_{x \to $q^+} f(x) = $right_sym \).
$BR $SPACE $BR

To find \( \ \displaystyle \lim_{x \to $q^-} f(x) \) we consider what happens to the function when \( x \) is slightly less than \( $q \).  Again we can use a table to investigate this behavior:
$BR
$BCENTER
\{ begintable(6) \}
\{ row ( "\( x \)", @z , "$q" ) \}
\{ row ( "\( f(x) \)", @l, "Undefined" ) \}
\{ endtable() \}
$ECENTER
$BR
From the table we can see that \( \ \displaystyle \lim_{x \to $q^-} f(x) = $left_sym \).
$BR
END_SOLUTION

      
ENDDOCUMENT();